Trinity Site explosion at .025 seconds.<br>
<br>
On July 16 1945, in a desert at Alamogordo, New Mexico, a mushroom cloud rose into the air. This was the Trinity Test and it marked the dawn of the Atomic Age. The World would never be quite the same again. Emitting an eerie blue glow due to high levels of radiation, the explosion of the first atomic bomb was witnessed by awestruck Los Alamos National Laboratory scientists.<br>
<br>
Stationed at the Trinity Base Camp, Enrico Fermi was one of those scientists. From a position about ten miles from the site of the explosion he estimated that the test corresponded to the kind of blast that would be produced by ten thousand tons of T.N.T.<br>
<br>
The next day on July 17, 1945 a petition was sent to the President of the United States by Scientists at the Chicago Metallurgical Laboratory. It begins as follows:<br>
<br>
Discoveries of which the people of the United States are not aware may affect the welfare of this nation in the near future. The liberation of atomic power which has been achieved places atomic bombs in the hands of the Army. It places in your hands, as Commander-in-Chief, the fateful decision whether or not to sanction the use of such bombs in the present phase of the war against Japan.  <br>
<br>
We, the undersigned scientists, have been working in the field of atomic power. Until recently we have had to fear that the United States might be attacked by atomic bombs during this war and that her only defense might lie in a counterattack by the same means. Today, with the defeat of Germany, this danger is averted and we feel impelled to say what follows:  <br>
<br>
The war has to be brought speedily to a successful conclusion and attacks by atomic bombs may very well be an effective method of warfare. We feel, however, that such attacks on Japan could not be justified, at least not unless the terms which will be imposed after the war on Japan were made public in detail and Japan were given an opportunity to surrender.  <br>
<br>
It goes on to describe the unique role of the US in leading the control of nuclear development Worldwide and the repercussions of failing to keep other nations down.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.wsmr.army.mil/paopage/Images/jumbo.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
On July 24, 1945 at 7:30 P.M. President Truman casually mentioned to Stalin that the US had a new weapon of unusual destructive force. The Russian Premier showed no special interest. All he said was that he was glad to hear it and hoped they would make good use of it against the Japanese. The President said later that Stalin's reply indicated no especial interest and that the Genaralissimo did not seem to have any conception of what Truman was talking about. It was simply another weapon and he hoped they would use it effectively. Five feet away Churchill watched the momentous talk taking place with the closest of attention. He knew what the President was going to do. What was vital to measure was its effect on Stalin. 'He seemed to be delighted....' reflected Churchill at a later date. <br>
As they were waiting for their cars the British PM found himself near Truman. 'How did it go?' he asked. 'He never asked a question,' replied Truman.<br>
<br>
 <br>
The new weapons are used on Hiroshima, then Nagasaki, leading to the end of World War II. The beginning of the Cold War then follows with the USSR's detonation of an atomic bomb in 1949. In the 1950's the construction of bomb shelters and the deployment of the first Intercontinental Ballistic Missiles by the United States in 1958 mark the start of nuclear proliferation. <br>
<br>
The 1960's saw France and China join the &quot;Nuclear Club&quot;. The Cuban Missile Crisis brings the world to the brink of a nuclear war and back. In 1968 an unpopular war in Vietnam and the rise of social demonstrations across the world present the backdrop for the Non-Proliferation Treaty in which the nuclear powers promise to bring about complete nuclear disarmament. Nobody is willing to dismantle all their nuclear armaments and trust the other club members to be honest though. That would be tantamount to suicide. Yet it is the underlying logic behind the Treaty. That one day, all weapons would be removed from military hands worldwide. A childish dream originating from ignorant if well intentioned mass protestors who want to turn back the clock but never can. The Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT) was signed on July 1, 1968 and entered into force on March 5, 1970. Central to the treaty is the concession of the Non-Nuclear Weapons States (NNWS or those without the Bomb) to refrain from acquiring the bomb and in exchange, the Nuclear Weapons States (NWS) agree to make progress on nuclear disarmament and provide unrestricted access to nuclear energy for non-military uses. The NPT has become the cornerstone of futile global disarmament efforts. How many nations signed it with the intention of breaking it is unknown. Most probably did so to appease the military might of the fearful nuclear club and ofcourse to get their hands on commercial reactors which would otherwise be denied them.<br>
<br>
The Cold War was at its height with Ronald Reagan declaring the USSR &quot;the Evil Empire.&quot; Reagan's Administration engineers a massive build-up of nuclear arms. In 1985 it's revealed that Israel may have up to 200 nuclear weapons stockpiled. By the end of the decade, the Cold War ended when Glasnost exploded into a mostly peaceful revolution across the former-Soviet block.<br>
<br>
The Utopian Dreamers of nuclear disarmament got a boost to their impossible cause when Ukraine, Kazahkstan and Belarus chose to give up their nuclear arsenals inherited from the former Soviet Union. More out of not wanting to pay costly maintenance than any willingness to aid the Utopians fantasies. Other nuclear weapons states do not follow suit ofcourse. By the end of the decade two other countries, India then Pakistan, test nuclear weapons. <br>
<br>
This decade began with the US proceeding on a nationwide missile defense system, abrogating the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty in the process. Thereby demonstrating the folly of thinking Treaties are unbreakable. Obviously they are only paper, and anyone can step away from them if it suits them to do so. <br>
<br>
The next worthless piece of paper, the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, opened for signature in 1996. Ratification of the treaty by the 44 Nuclear Weapons-Capable States is required before the treaty can enter into force. To date, only 2 of the Nuclear Weapons States, France and the United Kingdom have ratified the CTBT and three of the 44 Nuclear Weapons-Capable States, the DPRK, India and Pakistan, refuse to sign the treaty. The CTBT received a further setback in October 1999, when the US Senate failed to ratify the document. Preventing further nuclear weapons development is the clear aim of the CTBT, yet the US, Russia, and other Weapons States proceed to develop new nuclear weapons using computer simulations and subcritical underground nuclear testing. Although not a full nuclear weapons test, subcritical testing violates the absurd rules of the CTBT. Why is everybody cheating? Because they don't want to fall behind everyone else ofcourse.  <br>
<br>
What nobody thought about at the beginning of the Atomic Age was the infinite power of human determination and hatred. The prospect that one day the bomb would fall into terrorist hands. We are still not prepared for such a day. The attitude has always been that Nuclear Proliferation can somehow be controlled when clearly it cannot. Certainly not forever. How will we adapt to a nuclear terrorist's world? In the same way we should have adapted to the knowledge that atomic bombs are possible. By investing in domestic customs services above all else. Each nation must be responsible for policing nuclear material within its own borders and tracking that which passes through its borders. International policing is a waste of resources and should be abandoned. There is nothing callous about this. The nations of the World have had 57 years to prepare and can blame noone but themselves for ignoring the danger. Knowing an atomic bomb is possible means you are already halfway towards building one. The information is more available than ever. Nations are devising ingenious methods of secretly enriching Uranium they have either bought on the Blackmarket, taken from commercial reactors or simply mined. If you can make one bomb you can make a thousand given time. Time is what those who want the most devastating weapons now have. While the West bans itself from seriously researching nuclear weapons, others will gradually catch up to us and yes overtake our military might. This is a certainty. The bomb was developed out of fear that others would build it first. Why oh why didn't we stop to consider those who would secretly develop their own bombs while the nuclear club lets its arsenals age. <br>
<br>
This is only common sense. Technology that is banned by any nation invariably comes back to bite it in the rear. The British virtually outlawed cars at the turn of the century in favour of hoofs. The British Car industry has never caught up with Europe and the US as a consequence. The British admiralty saw no value in submarines. Much to the glee of German Uboat Captains later on. Perhaps if the Chinese had looked closer at the possibilities of their gun powder they would not have been so surprised by Western forces arriving with repeater rifles later on. Anything we ban will be researched elsewhere and the results of that work will be mostly unknown to us until the terrifying moment that it is used against us. This applies to any technology but the consequences of giving up on the most devastating weapon ever devised is particularly frightening. That's how the real World operates. As long as humans can think they will disagree on matters. As long as differences exist there will be hate and war. If we continue to underestimate the ingenuity of other nations in hiding nuclear research we will pay a very heavy price one day.<br>
<br>
The answer is not to try and bottle the nuclear genie but to embrace it. There is a flip side to nuclear technology. Peaceful applications of nuclear research become available along with its weapon potential. In opening Pandoras box we were so horrified at what came out that we immediately tried to close it. What we didn't realise and still don't, is that the box can never truly be closed. The knowledge that nuclear bombs are possible will always be out there, and we do ourselves harm by pretending otherwise. It's time we stopped trying to close the box and actually looked further inside. Delving deeper we may find 'hope'. Because with familiarity comes understanding and fear is born of ignorance. Nuclear weapons are still the only defence against nuclear weapons. The better we understand this technology the more easily we can defend against it. <br>
<br>
The way to survival is straightforward. To make nuclear bombs you need fissile material. Enriched Uranium or Plutonium. The heaviest most radioactive metals on Earth. Easily identified by radiation detectors, metal detectors and X-ray machines. If we are serious about adapting to survive the Atomic Age then we must screen every ship container, every bag, every person entering our borders. Satellites must monitor areas where nuclear material resides. Military personelle should be placed at commercial nuclear power plants. Nuclear Police must be created and given wide ranging powers of search and arrest. If this sounds extreme and unecessary then think back to Sept 11 and ask yourself what might be happening behind closed doors all around the World right now even as you read this electronic article. Nobody foresaw the collapse of the World Trade Centre buildings and partial collapse of the Pentagon. Those attacks were achieved with box cutters and suicide pilots. Al-Qaida is only one of many terrorist groups with billions of dollars to support their agendas.<br>
<br>
It is a common misconception that nuclear elements last thousands of years. Plutonium has a halflife of only 14 years. This means that it loses half its potency every 14 years and our decades old nuclear arsenals will gradually vanish without frequent replacement fissionables. Missiles don't last forever either. Eventually they will get scrapped. As other nations build up nuclear arsenals, we are letting ours slip away. When the balance of power shifts from the West, our enemies wont fear us at all. A Super Power can threaten a response. So can a nation of equal might. Weaker nations must rely on mercy from their enemies. If we ban ourselves from researching or creating new technologies, then we effectively ban ourselves from the great game of international competition. We relegate ourselves to the dustbin of once great civilisations and watch others step in to fill the void. How far might we fall? Ask modern day Romans and Egyptians who have forgotten the Age of Empires completely.<br>
<br>
